<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 93 / Brussels warns post services: Pricing tactics anger couriers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SEVEN European postal services, including the British Post Office, came
under pressure from the European Commission yesterday to improve the
fairness and transparency of their charges, following complaints that they
are stifling competition from private operators.
Brussels said it had opened a formal inquiry into allegations that national
postal services in Germany, Belgium, France, Finland, Sweden, Switzerland
and Britain were deliberately hampering the 'remailing' of bulk mail by
private couriers.
The move comes before EC telecommunications ministers next month discuss the
outcome of talks on the Commission's outline plan for further liberalisation
of EC postal services. The International Express Couriers' Conference
complained to Brussels that postal authorities had changed the way they
charge for remailed items, which couriers are paid to collect from large
clients and deliver to countries where tariffs are lower.
In particular, the IECC said national administrations had begun to take into
account each item, rather than charge for the weight of the whole delivery.
It also said letters posted outside the country where the sender was based
were often returned or subjected to additional charges.
Mr Karel Van Miert, EC competition commissioner, said he hoped the complaint
could be resolved in the context of debates over the Commission's
liberalisation plans. Commission officials said postal administrations had
already begun work on making their costs, and thus the calculation of their
fees, more transparent.
Royal Mail said the EC had not criticised its general postage charges, but
had merely taken a further step in examining a complaint filed five years
ago about remailing. 'Remailing represents a situation which could become a
threat to our customers,' Royal Mail added. 'If the practice became
widespread, it could result in a majority of our loyal UK customers having
to pay higher postage prices to subsidise the minority of customers who are
evading UK domestic postage.'
</TEXT>
