<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 93 / Moslems relent on Srebrenica refugees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER, Diplomatic Editor and Agencies
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOSLEM authorities in the besieged Bosnian town of Srebrenica last night
relented and said they would let 1,600 women and children be evacuated
today.
.Their move follows determined action by General Philippe Morillon,
commander of United Nations forces in Bosnia, to break the humanitarian
impasse in Srebrenica, where twice in the last few days local Moslem
commanders have refused to allow convoys bringing in food and medicines to
the besieged eastern Bosnian town to evacuate thousands of old and wounded
people, women and children on their way back.
The local Moslem leaders had taken their decision in spite of the suffering
of the inhabitants of Srebrenica, whose population has swollen to 60,000 by
refugees from nearby Serb-occupied areas, because they believed it
contributed to the Serbs' policy of 'ethnic cleansing.'
The Serbs make no secret of their desire to incorporate the Srebrenica
region, which has been allocated by international mediators Cyrus Vance and
Lord Owen to the Bosnian Moslems, into a Serb-dominated province.
Last night Gen Morillon was heading for Srebrenica with four armoured cars,
followed by a contingent of Canadian troops. Moslem officials have indicated
that, if Srebrenica can be assured of UN protection in the guise of a
Canadian 'blue helmets' unit, they would be prepared to allow resumption of
UN evacuation.
The Bosnian Serb army command had been informed of Gen Morillon's mission,
but had not yet given its reply.
In Brussels meanwhile, the approval by Nato ambassadors of final plans for
using alliance fighters to enforce the UN no-fly zone over Bosnia, hit a
last-minute snag as a result of French concerns about the rules of
engagement.
French officials said France was anxious to make sure the no-fly zone was
not enforced in such a provocative way that it drew everyone into a war.
As a result, it is possible that final approval will be delayed until today
or next week.
In Sarajevo, snipers killed four civilians trying to cross the airport
runway after Bosnian commanders failed to sign a safe passage deal.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BAZ  Bosnia-Hercegovina, East Europe.
</CN>
