FT  07 APR 93 / International Company News: Dutch paper group down 75%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMSTERDAM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
KNP BT, the big Dutch paper and packaging group created out of a three-way
merger last month, saw net profits plummet by nearly 75 per cent in 1992,
underlying the difficult market conditions.
Combined pro forma net profit for the three merger partners - the Dutch
companies KNP, Buhrmann-Tetterode and VRG - fell to Fl 116m (Dollars 64.6m)
from Fl 443m in 1991. If extraordinary items are excluded, net profit
declined by 64 per cent to Fl 175m from Fl 489m a year earlier.
Overall, group operating profit was down 42 per cent at Fl 538m. Sales
increased by 2.2 per cent to Fl 11.76bn.
