<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 93 / House prices increase in linewith recent sales revival
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOUSE PRICES in the UK rose by 1.2 per cent in March, the largest monthly
increase for four years, the Halifax Building Society said yesterday.
The seasonally adjusted figures suggest that the recent revival in sales
reported by house builders, estate agents and building societies is starting
to have an impact on prices - although the society warned against reading
too much into one month's figures.
Mr Tony Baldry, environment minister, nonetheless welcomed the figures,
saying they provided further encouraging signs of recovery in the
construction industry.
Halifax, Britain's largest mortgage lender, said: 'Whilst this a very
encouraging sign that the housing market is beginning to recover we will
need a few more months of strong activity and stable or rising prices before
we can be confident that a sustained upturn is under way.'
Halifax said the 1.2 per cent rise was the biggest since March 1989 when
prices increased by 1.6 per cent. Before seasonal adjustment the figure
represented a 2.2 per cent increase.
Nationwide, the second largest building society, last week reported that
house prices had risen by 1 per cent in March compared with February, on an
unadjusted basis.
Despite this, the average price of a house in the UK of Pounds 61,510 last
month was still 5.2 per cent lower than in March last year.
Halifax, however, was encouraged that the rise in inquiries from potential
purchasers seen since the beginning of this year was starting to work
through to increased mortgage applications and offers.
The value of new commitments to mortgages by building societies rose by 40
per cent in February from January.
House builders say net reservations - agreed sales on which a deposit has
been paid less cancellations - have risen by between a fifth and a quarter
compared with the first 13 weeks of last year.
Halifax said that despite last month's increase it was sticking to its
forecast that prices would generally remain flat during the next few months
before starting to rise towards the end of this year. Nevertheless, some
stability seemed to be returning to prices, slightly earlier than expected.
The team which previously prepared construction forecasts for the National
Economic Development Office says the decline in construction output this
year is likely to be less than expected because of the recovery in the
housing market.
JFC Construction Forecasts said yesterday it had reduced its forecast for
the decline in output to 1.5 per cent from 2 per cent previously. It said
housing repair, maintenance and improvement work was likely to increase
because of increased confidence in the market. This would boost total
construction output.
</TEXT>
