<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
War crimes are always perpetrated by the vanquished, never by the victors.
This is such a truism that you can turn the formula round and say to anyone
who still doubts that the Americans lost in Vietnam: of course they did,
their war crimes, from Hanoi to My Lai, are world famous. Who ever heard of
Vietcong war crimes? Thus the repeated attempts decades later, to turn the
civilian raids by RAF Bomber Command into a 'war crime' are a waste of time
since they were carried out by the winning side. Nevertheless Timewatch sets
out to whip up another argument (7.45 BBC2). Anybody with long experience in
almost any line of work will tell you that a good old 'un will out-perform
several good young 'uns. Pop music? Of course: look at Mick Jagger and Tina
Turner, combined age well over 100. Dispatches considers the absurdity of
'ageism' and points out the difficulties in everyone living longer yet being
retired earlier (9.00 C4). QED reports on the piddock, a shellfish which
glows in the dark and 'looks set to revolutionise the treatment of diabetes,
arthritis and heart disease' (9.30 BBC1).
</TEXT>
