<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 93 / Customs admits error over VAT rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE commissioners of Customs and Excise have admitted exceeding their powers
in introducing regulations on the administration of VAT from January 26.
In a memorandum to the Commons committee on statutory instruments, the
commissioners accept that they erred in introducing rules before the
enabling statutory instrument was laid before parliament.
The regulations were intended to remedy an inadvertent striking out of vital
rules concerning input tax deduction.
The committee found that the VAT (general) (amendment) regulations were
ultra vires - beyond the commissioners' powers - to the extent that the
rules purported to have a limited retrospective effect.
It rebuked the commissioners for not notifying Miss Betty Boothroyd, the
speaker of the Commons, and Lord Mackay, the lord chancellor, that the
instrument came into operation before it was laid before parliament.
The committee also criticised the commissioners for failing to issue the
regulations free to people known to have purchased a copy of the defective
instrument.
The commissioners, explaining why they felt the need for urgency in giving
effect to the regulations, said the whole of the system under which input
tax deduction is made by taxable persons would have been jeopardised without
the re-introduction of provisions which had been 'inadvertently revoked'.
