<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 93 / Customs admits exceeding powers on VAT
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE commissioners of Customs and Excise have admitted exceeding their powers
in introducing regulations on the administration of valued added tax from
January 26 1993.
In a memorandum to the Commons committee on statutory instruments, the
commissioners accept that they erred in introducing rules before the
enabling statutory instrument was laid before parliament. The regulations
were intended to remedy an inadvertent striking out of vital rules
concerning input tax deduction.
The committee found that the VAT (general) (amendment) regulations were
ultra vires - beyond the commissioners' powers - to the extent that the
rules purported to have a limited retrospective effect.
The error would have been avoided if the regulations had not specified
January 26 1993 - the day they were made - as the date for commencement or
had specified commencement 'forthwith', the Commons committee said.
The committee rebuked the commissioners for not notifying Miss Betty
Boothroyd, the speaker of the Commons, and Lord Mackay, the lord chancellor,
that the instrument came into operation before it was laid before
parliament.
Dismissing the commissioners' claim that no 'useful purpose' would have been
served by giving such notification, the Commons committee insisted that it
could accept that a government department 'can give itself a dispensation
from the need to explain the reasons'.
The committee also criticised the commissioners for failing to issue the
regulations free to people known to have purchased a copy of the defective
instrument.
The commissioners, explaining why they felt the need for urgency in giving
effect to the regulations, said the whole of the system under which input
tax deduction is made by taxable persons would have been jeopardised without
the re-introduction of provisions which had been 'inadvertently revoked'.
</TEXT>
