<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 93 / Labour floats plan for recovery partnership
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN the document Making Britain's Future, Labour proposes a wide-ranging and
radical programme of change as the basis for addressing the decline in the
industrial base through partnership between the government and industry.
These are the main proposals and questions on which Labour will be
consulting over the next 12 months:
New commercial structures
How can stakeholders in a company such as employees best be represented in
its governance?
What is the best balance of power between executive and non-executive
directors?
Should the UK follow the model of the European two-tier board structure,
where an executive board responsible for management is accountable to a
supervisory board representing stakeholders?
There should be incentives for longer-term equity ownership, including a
review of the tax regime.
The law on takeovers should be reformed 'to improve the stability of
industrial companies and to reduce the diversion of funds into acquisition
rather than investment'. The burden of proof should be on the predator
company to show that a hostile takeover is in the national interest.
Bankruptcy law needs overhauling. What lessons can be learned from the US
system of filing for protection against creditors forcing closure?
There should be an inquiry into auditing standards and accountancy
conventions. Research and development should be treated as capital
investment rather than revenue spending.
An investment drive
Could building societies have a role in mobilising savings for investment in
industry as well as property?
An industrial investment unit should be set up at the Department of Trade
and Industry.
Pension fund law should be reformed to provide greater accountability of
managers to trustees.
What changes in the law would facilitate greater investment by pension funds
in productive capacity in Britain? How could they develop portfolios that
contained more direct investment in British industry?
Should capital allowances be used to encourage backing for long-term
investment and product development? Could investment in research be
increased by enhancing the existing allowances with tax credits? What new
institutions are needed to promote more direct investment in industry and
bridge the investment gaps left by banks?
How can private-sector finance be attracted in to public-sector projects to
strengthen the infrastructure?
A training levy should be imposed on companies which do not invest in
skills.
Strength to the regions
There should be a network of regional development agencies to support local
companies and co-ordinate inward investment.
How could banks and financial institutions develop decision centres at
regional level with real freedom to work with regional agencies?
Should agencies be able to float their own bonds?
Getting government backing
There should be a statement on how new policy affects industry.
Within the European Community, Britain must resist the transfer of resources
away from research and development, transport and infrastructure to
agriculture.
Greater use should be made of the European Investment Bank.
</TEXT>
