<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 93 / Shorter degree courses proposed
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
UNIVERSITIES are con-sidering radical changes to the academic year to
increase their potential student intake.
Lord Flowers, chairman of the Committee of Inquiry into the Academic Year,
said yesterday that extended summertime teaching could hold the key to
reducing the present overcrowding.
Summer schools could allow degree courses to be completed in less than the
normal three years, an interim report by the Flowers committee says.
Mr John Patten, education secretary, welcomed the proposals. 'I look forward
to a more flexible academic year in the future,' he told the first annual
conference of the Higher Education Funding Council for England.
'It would be welcome if, at the same time as enhancing the quality of higher
education, such changes to the academic year had the effect of increasing
the numbers of students who could be taught.'
Lord Flowers told 140 heads of universities and colleges at the conference
in Birmingham that institutions would be consulted before a final report was
submitted by the autumn.
Many universities and colleges were already introducing or planning changes
which would radically alter the conventional academic year of three 10-week
terms, he said.
Unions representing academic staff warned that changes under consideration
would require a 'massive' injection of extra resources.
'University staff have already paid the price for the under-funded expansion
of student numbers,' said the AUT/Natfhe confederation.
</TEXT>
