<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 93 / MMC recommends ITV changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Monopolies and Mergers Commission yesterday recommended significant
amendments to the way the ITV network is run. It aims to ensure more
flexible arrangements between ITV companies and independent producers.
The decision was welcomed by the ITV companies, independent producers and
the Independent Television Commission, all of which had been in conflict
over programme rights.
The commission backed the finding last December by the Office of Fair
Trading that ITV proposals for running the national network were
anti-competitive.
It said there should be no rigid limits on the acquisition of programme
rights, and rejected the OFT's insistence that when an independent producer
agrees a programme deal with the ITV network, the network should retain
exclusive UK rights over the programme for no more than five years, with an
optional additional two years.
Instead the commission has laid down guidelines based on the network centre
being granted exclusive UK broadcasting rights for up to five years, with
longer periods possible through options.
The commission said it had introduced guidelines rather than specifying a
fixed maximum period of rights to reflect the different circumstances that
may arise in practice.
The ITC yesterday warned ITV that it would monitor the new guidelines, which
in effect make terms subject to negotiation.
The commission also modified an OFT recommendation that producers should
have the right to be commissioned by the network rather than having to work
through a sponsoring ITV company.
An independent producer will be able to agree a deal directly with the
network centre. The producer will then enter a three-way contract with the
centre and an ITV company, whose role will be limited to ensuring the
programme complies with the requirements of the ITC.
The commission also removed a barrier imposed by the OFT to ITV companies
having options on series and programme formats, which had been condemned by
the television industry.
Mr John Woodward, director of the group, said he was delighted at the
commission's verdict, but added: 'It looks more like a multiple car accident
for ITV. But . . . if they're happy I'm happy.'
Mr Andrew Quinn, chief executive of ITV, said the commission's document was
'a very very practical piece of common sense.'
The report was also welcomed by Mr Leslie Hill, chairman of Central
Independent Television, who also chairs the ITV steering committee on the
issue. He said: 'The onus is on us not to abuse the system otherwise we will
get investigated again.'
Editorial comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
