<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 93 / Earnings forecasts 'over-optimistic'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ANALYSTS' forecasts of earnings are unreliable in predicting the figures
companies report and are nearly always over-optimistic, a study has found.
The predictions become increasingly less reliable the further away from the
results announcement they are. And more than one year before a company
reports they are little more accurate than drawing a straight line from the
previous set of figures, according to Strathclyde University re-search
presented at the conference.
The research supports recent anecdotal evidence of the inaccuracy of
investment houses' research, such as recommendations to buy the shares of
Queens Moat House hours before they were suspended, or Polly Peck days
before the company collapsed. The study was based on a database containing
69,258 forecasts of earnings per share made by analysts between January 1988
and December 1990, compared with the reported earnings of the companies
studied.
</TEXT>
