FT  07 APR 93 / Rail talks expected in attempt to avert strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TALKS BETWEEN British Rail and the RMT transport union are expected to try
to avert the second 24-hour rail strike planned for Friday April 16.
The RMT's executive yesterday decided to allow a breathing space before the
next stoppage is due to take place so that a 'negotiated settlement' might
be reached with BR.
Mr Jimmy Knapp, RMT general secretary, said yesterday: 'The opportunity is
there if BR want to take it.' He stressed that his union's dispute is with
the British Railways board and not the travelling public. 'As a responsible
trade union we respect the fact that many thousands of families and
individuals will be setting off to enjoy a break this (Easter) weekend. We
do not intend to disrupt that holiday,' he said.
Mr Knapp added that the RMT was 'willing to resume negotiations to find a
resolution of the dispute'. The union is asking BR for a guarantee that it
will not seek compulsory redundancies among its members and for a ban on the
employment of contractors on the railway network.
Mr Paul Watkinson, BR group personnel director, expressed dismay at the
decision to hold a second 24-hour strike and said he would be in touch with
the union to see 'once again whether there is scope to resolve the situation
through serious talking with a will to reach a solution'.
</TEXT>
