<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 93 / Computerisation fails to ease passport delays
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPUTERISATION has failed to cut the costs and time taken to issue
passports by the extent expected, the National Audit Office says.
The government expenditure watchdog says in a report published today that
the time taken by the Passport Agency to issue a passport was supposed to
have been cut to five working days. Although the new system has been
installed in all passport offices, it takes 20 working days to process an
application in peak periods and 10 days at other times.
In spite of advertising to encourage applications in off-peak periods, they
continue to be concentrated in the first six months of the year.
The NAO says that the agency could improve its service by differential
pricing to smooth the flow of work through the year - for example, by
reducing the price of a passport in off-peak times.
But the agency is reluctant to consider differential pricing because a cut
large enough to be effective might shift all demand to off-peak months.
The report also says that the Home Office Nationality Division has failed to
achieve its target of processing citizenship applications within 12 months.
Average waiting time in January 1993 was 20 months, down from 33 months in
March 1991 but still higher than in 1987.
Manpower Planning in the Home Office. HMSO. Pounds 6.70.
</TEXT>
