<HEADLINE>
FT  07 APR 93 / Talks on Ukraine's missiles at dead end
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRYSTIA FREELAND and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KIEV
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NEGOTIATIONS between Ukraine and Russia over the future of the nuclear
weapons on Ukrainian territory have reached a 'dead end', Ukraine's
President Leonid Kravchuk said yesterday.
To resolve the stalemate, he has suggested to Russian President Boris
Yeltsin that the issue be discussed by the Ukrainian and Russian prime
ministers.
Mr Kravchuk rejected Russia's accusation that Ukraine wanted to be a nuclear
power. But he reaffirmed Ukraine's claim to ownership of strategic nuclear
missiles on its territory. An alternative of granting Russia ownership of
the Ukrainian missiles was 'unacceptable' because Ukraine could not permit a
foreign military presence on its soil.
Radiation leaked from a plant in Siberia yesterday after an explosion in a
tank containing uranium, Reuter reports. No casualties were reported in the
incident at the Tomsk-7 complex, one of three facilities in Russia for
processing spent nuclear fuel.
</TEXT>
