<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Armed gangs block Papua gold
project
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CRA, the Australian mining group, has abandoned plans to produce gold in the
Mount Kare region of Papua New Guinea, drawing renewed attention to the
touchy relationship between the government and foreign resources companies.
The withdrawal, announced in Port Moresby on Sunday, comes three weeks after
CRA evacuated Mount Kare, claiming that staff were being threatened by rival
gangs of armed landowners.
The group rejected demands for an apology from the government, which claimed
that the evacuation was related to a financial dispute between CRA and
Kare-Puga Development Corporation (KDC), the landowners company.
CRA agreed in October to transfer to KDC its 51 per cent stake in a joint
venture which owns an alluvial goldfield in the area around Mount Kare. The
remaining shares in the joint venture are owned by KDC.
The group had intended to retain the rights to prospect for hard-rock gold
deposits, but appears to have given up hope that the security problems in
the area can be overcome.
CRA said that 'disproportionately high costs,' had been incurred at 'great
effort and risk,' in an attempt to stabilise the Mount Kare project in the
interests of landowners and the good name of the Papua New Guinea mining
industry.
</TEXT>
