<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COPPER touched five-week lows on the LME, helping to push ALUMINIUM down to
14 1/2 -month lows. Further losses are likely in both metals, dealers said.
Copper's decline stemmed from the fall below Dollars 2,155-Dollars 2,160 for
three-month metal. Dealers will be looking for support around Dollars 2,130
to hold, ahead of tomorrow's April option declarations, although falls
towards long-term support near Dollars 2,100 are possible. GOLD was still
consolidating its position on the London bullion market and would probably
remain for now between Dollars 338 and Dollars 340 a troy ounce, dealers
said. Arabica COFFEE was lower at midday in New York after scoring
life-of-contract lows across the board in early trading. There was no buying
interest and volume was thin. One analyst said the recent break below 59.20
cents for May had set the stage for a move to 48 cents over the next few
weeks. In London the May robusta contract managed to hold key support at
Dollars 852 a tonne. The only possible supportive factor was the likely
absence of origins owing to the imminent Easter holidays.
Compiled from Reuters
