FT  06 APR 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Bafokeng chief to join Impala
Platinum board
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE GRADUAL return to health of Impala Platinum, South Africa and the
world's second largest producer, continues with the announcement yesterday
that acting chief Mokgwaro George Molotlegi had accepted an invitation to
join Impala's board as a representative of the Bafokeng tribe.
The Bafokeng tribe is an important player as it owns the land that Impala
mines. Doubt has in the past been cast over the security of Impala's lease
owing to disputes about who represents the Bafokeng tribe.
Mr Michael McMahon, executive chairman of Impala commented yesterday: 'This
is a significant step in furthering our relationship with the Bafokeng
tribe, who are a vital part of our operations.'
The Bafokeng do not own equity in Impala, but in terms of a royalty
agreement are entitled to 13 per cent of taxable income.
