<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / Government Bonds: Flood of gilts leads to a bout of
indigestion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB and LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UK GOVERNMENT bonds fell by up to  3/4 of a point at the long end as the
recent heavy supply weighed on the gilt market.
After last Wednesday's Pounds 3bn auction of 20-year stock, the Bank of
England issued Pounds 600m of 10-year gilts, and on Friday it announced a
further Pounds 650m of conventional and index-linked stock for sale.
Dealers said a call for Pounds 1.8bn on partly-paid stock yesterday provided
an additional burden for the market.
'The market is coming to terms with the fact that about Pounds 5bn of calls
fall due in the next six weeks,' said Mr John Kendall, economist at Baring
Sterling Bonds.
Mr John Shepperd, economist at S. G. Warburg Securities, said: 'The auction
was well-absorbed, but the new tranches came a bit to soon - there's been
some consolidation and now there's some indigestion.'
The two new tap stocks announced on Friday include Pounds 250m of the 7 1/4
per cent gilt due 1998 and Pounds 150m of 2 1/2 per cent index-linked stock
due 2020.
Dealers reported some buying of both stocks, although neither tap stock was
exhausted.
The 7 1/4 per cent gilt due 1998 fell  1/8 of a point to 102 1/16 by late
afternoon while the 9 per cent gilt due 2008 dropped  23/32 to 106 19/32 .
Separately, figures released yesterday by the Bank showed that foreigners
bought Pounds 1.03bn of gilts in February, following two months of net
selling of UK government debt.
GERMAN government bonds ended firmer, ignoring comments from the Bundesbank
president that short-term interest rates were unlikely to be cut imminently.
Mr Helmut Schlesinger was quoted in the Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung as
saying that the Bundesbank should not undertake too rapid an easing of key
interest rates.
Bund futures opened at 95.28 and traded in a range of 95.24 to 95.49, ending
the day at 95.34.
US TREASURY prices were slightly higher and the rest of the yield curve
mostly flat as traders marked time before US consumer and wholesale price
data is released later this week. The recent rise in long-bond yields has
focused attention on inflation risks. The US will report its index of March
wholesaler prices on Thursday. On Friday, a market holiday, data on March US
consumer prices will be reported. Traders expect both figures to be up 0.3
of a percentage point.
By late afternoon, the Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond was  11/32 higher
at 101 5/32 , yielding 7.028 per cent. Among shorter-dated maturities, the
two-year note was up  1/16 at 99 7/8 to yield 3.924 per cent, and the
3-month Treasury bill was also down  1/16 at 2.90, yielding 2.94 per cent.
The Federal Reserve executed three-day system repurchase agreements today,
injecting liquidity into the banking system. The federal funds were trading
at 3 1/8 per cent late in the day. Traders said the Fed requested fixed
collateral for the repos, a factor that is tied to the fact the US is
bumping up its congressionally-mandated debt ceiling.
A Republican fillibuster in the Senate over President Bill Clinton's
stimulus package continues to block action to raise the debt ceiling. As a
result, today's weekly sale of Dollars 22.4 bn in 13-week and 26-week
Treasury bills has been postponed. JAPANESE government bond prices fell
back, taking their cue from the continued rally in the stock market and
uncertainty over the extent to which the government's supplementary budget
would be funded by bond issuance.
The futures contract opened at 108.31, down from Friday's close of 108.53,
and fell to a low of 107.97 before ending at 108.16 in Tokyo.
The bond market remained weak despite the yen's continued strength against
the US dollar. The yen/dollar rate firmed to a new high of 113.30 before
moving back to 113.75.
</TEXT>
