<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / International Company News: Embraer follows industry trend
with Dollars 258m loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BILL HINCHBERGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EMBRAER, the state-owned Brazilian aircraft maker, reflected the continuing
trouble in the world aerospace industry by posting a Dollars 258m loss in
1992. In 1991, the group lost Dollars 235m.
Sales were Dollars 312m last year, down from Dollars 402m in 1991 and
Dollars 582m in 1990.
The company blamed the poor figures on the recession in Brazil and the US,
Embraer's most important market. It also cited reduced government spending
on military aircraft due to cuts in the Brazilian air force budget.
It laid off 2,468 last year, bringing the two year redundancy total to
6,800, a 54 per cent cut in the workforce.
Embraer's best-known product is the EMB-120 Brasilia, a 30-seat regional
aircraft. It accounts for about half of Embraer's sales, but last year sales
fell to just 22 units, down from 31 in 1991 and 48 in 1990.
In a speech to employees earlier this year, Mr Ozires Silva, Embraer
president, was optimistic about prospects for 1993.
He said he was encouraged by increased demand for aircraft in South America
and the possibility of increasing revenues from providing services to other
companies. He predicted that between 2 and 3 per cent of sales might come
from the services segment this year.
Embraer is on the government's short-list for privatisation, but before the
move can go ahead the company must resolve an issue involving a group of
creditors who hold debentures convertible into non-voting stock.
If all of the debentures were converted, the government's majority voting
share could be reduced to as little as 3 per cent of total equity.
Copesul, a Brazilian petrochemical company privatised last May, unveiled an
increase in profits to Dollars 42.5m for 1992. The supplier of raw materials
for one of Brazil's three petrochemical hubs, it earned Dollars 30m in 1991.
</TEXT>
