<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / International Company News: Marriott shareholders in lawsuit
against company
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A GROUP of preferred shareholders of Marriott, the hotels and management
services group, has filed a suit against the company and its management,
Reuter reports from Washington.
The group says a corporate reorganisation would take away 'the vast bulk of
Marriott's income-producing assets'.
That, the plaintiffs said, would leave them with virtually all of the
depressed property assets and the bulk of its large interest expense.
The suit was filed in Delaware Chancery Court April 2 by H. B. Korenvaes
Investment, the President and Fellows of Harvard College, AKT Associates and
UBS Securities.
The group holds the equivalent of a 6.4 per cent stake, or about 6.85m
common shares, in Marriott. The stake includes 2.2m preferred shares
convertible into common stock.
'The plaintiffs are to receive nothing in this reorganisation plan except an
as-yet undisclosed reduction in their conversion price,' the group said in
the suit.
The plaintiffs are seeking an injunction to stop the reorganisation being
carried out.
</TEXT>
