<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / UK Company News: Decline in tobacco profits leaves T&amp;S 6%
lower
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A DROP in profits from tobacco retailing and from shop disposals lay behind
a fall of more than 6 per cent at T&amp;S Stores last year.
The pre-tax figure declined from Pounds 13.4m to Pounds 12.5m on sales up 10
per cent at Pounds 345.3m (Pounds 314.2m).
Operating profits were ahead to Pounds 12.6m (Pounds 12.4m), but lower
profits from disposals, reduced interest income and a charge for
reorganisation hit the pre-tax line.
Mr Kevin Threlfall, chairman and chief executive, said it had been a
frustrating year. 'A number of growth opportunities came to nothing as
either price, quality or a combination of both proved to be a stumbling
block.'
The group remains keen to expand its convenience store network.
It has admitted that it looked at the Circle K chain, recently sold to
Watson &amp; Philip for Pounds 21m.
The Dillons convenience stores increased their profits to Pounds 3.89m
(Pounds 3.12m) on sales of Pounds 68m (Pounds 52.1m). Eleven stores were
opened, mainly in the second half.
However, the advance in convenience stores was undone by a fall in profits
from Pounds 3.76m to Pounds 3.16m, on sales of Pounds 175.3m (Pounds 165.4m)
at Supercigs. Margins were squeezed by increased competition.
To try to improve the business, the discount formula was being rolled out
from cigarettes to magazines and greetings cards.
At the Dillons newsagents, profits were flat at Pounds 5.59m (Pounds 5.57m)
on sales of Pounds 102.1m (Pounds 96.7m).
T&amp;S said Pounds 1m of annual costs had been taken out of the business. At
the year-end the group's overdraft was Pounds 9.5m, compared with Pounds
12m.
The company said this was seasonal and it often had up to Pounds 10m cash in
the bank.
Earnings per share slipped to 15.17p (15.71p).
The final dividend goes up to 3.5p to give a total of 5.9p (5.5p).
COMMENT
T&amp;S has some defensive virtues, but in a weak market these have not been
sufficient to keep earnings moving ahead. Growth is seen as coming mainly
from acquisitions, but it is a long time since the big leap forward made in
spring 1989 with the acquisition of Preedy and Dillons from Next. Analysts
are not only holding their breath waiting for the next deal - and the
anticipated issue of paper - but also on the outcome of the discount
magazines experiment. Previous attempts have fallen foul of the wholesalers.
T&amp;S believes it has the muscle to pull it off and that scrutiny of the trade
by the MMC will keep the wholesalers on their best behaviour. Because of a
sharply rising tax charge, the group would have to sprint this year to stay
level on earnings per share. Profits are forecast to rise to more than
Pounds 13m, giving a prospective p/e of 12-13 on yesterday's close of 173p.
At this discount to the market, it is well worth holding.
</TEXT>
