<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / UK Company News: James Capel directors quit over losses on
venture fund
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THREE SENIOR directors of James Capel, the UK-based stockbroker owned by
HSBC, resigned yesterday over losses of up to Pounds 16m on an eastern
European venture capital fund.
The three were Mr James Fergusson, the broker's managing director, Mr Peter
Green, head of international operations, and Mr John Webster, head of
Capel's New York office.
Capel did not announce the reasons for the resignations, but all are
believed to have been linked to the failure of New Europe Hotels, a company
launched at the end of 1990 to raise money for hotel developments in eastern
Europe.
The company's shares were sold mainly through James Capel's New York office,
and two Capel executives joined the New Europe board.
The company collapsed last year, leaving investors with what is thought to
have been almost a total write-off. Capel is believed to have compensated
investors who bought shares through its New York office, at a cost to the
broker of as much as Pounds 16m.
Capel's Pounds 7.5m operating profit for last year, after restructuring and
after charges, was struck after the compensation costs, the company said.
At the time New Europe was launched, Mr Fergusson was head of Capel's
international operations and Mr Green ran the New York office.
Capel moved quickly yesterday to announce replacements for the three
departing executives. Mr Bob Benton, head of the UK institutional equities
division, was named as managing director; Mr Peter Maynard, former head of
compliance, is to become president of James Capel in New York; and Mr Duncan
Agar, an institutional equities salesman, has become head of the
non-European international desks in London.
After the announcement of a new deputy chairman last Friday, the
appointments amount to a substantial overhaul of the senior management of
the UK broker.
Mr Peter Letley, who joined Capel as finance director in 1988, was named
deputy chairman under Mr Bernard Asher, the HSBC director who took over the
Capel chairmanship two years ago.
Mr Benton said yesterday that the management upheaval did not imply any
change of direction at Capel.
The broker would continue its efforts to build trading and corporate finance
operations on the back of its established international equity distribution
business, he said.
</TEXT>
