<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / UK Company News: Confusion at SelecTV as legal probe is
completed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONFUSION still surrounded the affairs of SelecTV, the independent
television production company last night, following the completion of a
legal investigation by company solicitors Richards Butler.
SelecTV yesterday issued a statement saying that the report had drawn
attention to 'certain minor technical shortcomings in the formal
administration of the company.'
The release added that the appropriate remedial action had already been
taken.
Following the issuing of the statement, it is believed Richards Butler
contacted SelecTV suggesting that the statement may not have been wholly
supported by their draft report.
The main issue of contention seems to have been the fact that Richards
Butler regarded the matters under investigation as serious allegations.
SelecTV then issued a new press release saying it wanted to make clear that
the report it commissioned from Richards Butler included allegations
relating to Mr Allan McKeown, chief executive.
'After considering the report the board has concluded that Mr McKeown should
at once be exonerated from allegations of misfeasance,' the statement said.
Richards Butler, whose report has not been published, then withdrew its
reservations.
SelecTV confirmed yesterday that Mr Tony Brook, until recently deputy
chairman and managing director of TVS Entertainment, will join the board as
chairman. He is expected to head a remuneration committee which will look
into the salaries of directors. He is also expected to look at the rent paid
to Mr McKeown for the house he owns in central London which is used as
company offices.
The rent was the main item in a writ issued against Mr McKeown by Mr Michael
Buckley, chairman, with the knowledge of Mr Peter Laiser, an independent
director. The writ was never served and when it became public Mr Buckley was
ousted as chairman.
Last night Mr Buckley said that the events of the day confirmed his view
that the company should now appoint an independent firm of solicitors to
look at all the issues that led to the issuing of the writ.
A number of directors confirmed yesterday that an increase in the rent paid
to Mr McKeown from Pounds 40,000 to Pounds 80,000 a year had happened
without being recorded in board minutes. The directors insisted that they
all knew about the increase, which reflected the fact that other SelecTV
subsidiaries had moved into the house.
</TEXT>
