<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / Lufthansa in partnership talks with American Airlines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent and DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LUFTHANSA of Germany is in advanced partnership talks with American
Airlines, one of the 'big three' US carriers.
The negotiations reflect the German carrier's continuing efforts for a
strategic link with a large US carrier to boost its position on the
transatlantic airline market.
Lufthansa, which derives about 30 per cent of its annual revenue from its
North Atlantic routes, has faced particularly fierce competition across the
Atlantic following the acquisition of Pan American's European services,
which include a Frankfurt hub, by Atlanta-based Delta Air Lines.
Lufthansa said it was in talks with a number of US carriers, including
American Airlines although in the light of its financial difficulties it was
unlikely to take a share stake in any airline.
American acknowledged that 'at any time, we're talking to any number of
foreign carriers' about partnership arrangements, and said that such
discussions had been stepped up in the wake of the approval for the British
Airways-USAir code-sharing deal.
However, the US carrier stressed that talks were centred on joint marketing
and code-sharing arrangements, and were not likely to involve an equity
investment.
Lufthansa has stepped up its search for a US partner following British
Airways' Dollars 300m (Pounds 198m) investment in USAir and Air France's
co-operation agreement with Air Canada which, in turn, links the French
carrier to Continental Airlines of the US.
Lufthansa is also reacting to merger talks between Swissair, KLM Royal Dutch
Airlines, Scandinavian Airlines System and Austrian Airlines. Already, KLM
has a stake in Northwest, of the US, while Delta and Swissair have
cross-equity links.
Lufthansa held talks with both American Airlines and USAir about two years
ago.
</TEXT>
